            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rohan Espinoza is a product of San Francisco\u2019s Excelsior district, born to a Filipino father who could fix any engine and an Indian mother whose cooking could fill their small home with warmth. Growing up, Rohan was never one for books. While his parents preached the value of hard work, his focus was on taking things apart and, with less success, putting them back together. He was a tactile learner in a system that prized academic theory, and he scraped by to earn his high school diploma with a sigh of relief.\n\nAdrift after graduation, his turning point came not in a classroom but in a garage with a broken ten-speed bicycle he\u2019d bought for fifty dollars. The gears were jammed and the chain was a rusted mess. Instead of junking it, Rohan became obsessed. Hours spent on YouTube tutorials, asking questions at local bike co-ops, and working with borrowed tools transformed him. In successfully rebuilding that bike, he found a sense of purpose that school had never provided. He soon landed a job as an apprentice mechanic at a bustling shop in the Mission District.\n\nNow 25, Rohan is a respected mechanic, known for his patient and intuitive approach to repairs. His life is measured by the rhythmic whir of a well-oiled chain. He lives in a shared Richmond district apartment with two roommates, his $53,000 income a constant balancing act against the city's cost of living. His daily 2.5-mile commute is a dialogue with the city\u2014a challenging climb up one hill, a thrilling descent down another, a fluid weave through traffic. His social life is woven into the city\u2019s cycling culture, from weekend group rides through the Headlands to late-night chats with fellow gearheads at a local brewery.\n\nRohan\u2019s dream isn\u2019t a tech fortune; it\u2019s to one day open his own community-focused bike shop, a place where kids can learn to fix their own rides and everyone feels welcome. He feels a deep connection to the city\u2019s physical self\u2014its pavement, its inclines, its fog. For Rohan, San Francisco isn't a place of glittering start-ups, but a network of steep streets, dedicated bike lanes, and the quiet satisfaction of a perfectly tuned machine."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being twelve, huddled in the garage, trying to \"fix\" his mom\u2019s kitchen mixer. He\u2019d taken it apart, but the pieces wouldn't go back. Frustration welled up until his dad came in, smelling of motor oil, and didn't scold him. Instead, he sat down, handing Rohan the right screwdriver. \"Try again, *anak*,\" he'd said softly. It wasn't about the mixer; it was the quiet permission to break things in the pursuit of understanding them. It planted a seed of patience in his restless hands.\n\n2.\nHe was nineteen, and after weeks of grease-stained knuckles, it was done. He tentatively pushed the shifter on the ten-speed he'd rebuilt. Instead of a rusty grind, there was a crisp, satisfying *click*. The chain caught perfectly, the wheel spun true. In that one clean sound, he heard his own future. It was the first time he had ever created tangible order from chaos, a feeling of pure competence that washed away years of academic failure and whispered that he finally had a direction.\n\n3.\nJust an apprentice at twenty-one, a high-end carbon frame came in with a phantom creak that stumped the senior mechanics. Rohan stayed late, methodically disassembling it, trusting his hands over the manuals. He found it: a hairline fracture inside the bottom bracket shell, nearly invisible. Showing his boss the next morning, he felt a quiet surge of validation. It wasn't just about being right; it was the moment his intuition became a respected tool, earning him a place among the city\u2019s seasoned gearheads.\n\n4.\nLast winter, on a late ride home from the Mission. The fog was so dense it muffled the world, swallowing streetlights into soft glows. It was just him, his headlamp cutting a cone through the vapor, and the rhythmic hum of his tires on wet pavement. He felt less like he was moving through the city and more like a part of its quiet, breathing machinery. Climbing the hill into the Richmond, he felt an intense, peaceful ownership\u2014this physical city was his, in a way no one else understood.\n\n5.\nAbout six months ago, a kid came to the shop with a wobbly wheel, clutching a few crumpled dollars. The boss waved him off. On his break, Rohan found the boy outside and trued the wheel in five minutes, no charge. The kid\u2019s wide-eyed \"Whoa, thanks!\" held more weight than any paycheck. He realized his skill wasn't just for paying rent; it was a way to give back. The vague idea of his own community shop solidified then, shifting from a distant dream into a necessary plan."
